# Subject-Based Thinking (SBT)

Follow **Subject-Based Thinking** when designing, locating, and changing code: group everything that serves one **real-world or product concept** together so humans and agents share the same mental model. Background: [Dan Stephenson — Subject-Based Thinking](https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/subject-based-thinking-future-proof-architecture-human-dan-stephenson-vyzvc/).

SBT builds on ideas from domain-centric design, but the **subject** is the primary organizing principle: a conceptual anchor (user, project, plan, PowerVibe app, workflow, etc.), not only a bounded context name on a diagram.

## Core questions (before adding files or APIs)

1. **What is the subject?** (the thing the change is *about*)
2. **Can everything related to it live together?** (UI, hooks, client API, backend route handlers, types, repos, utils for that subject)

If the answer to (2) is “no,” prefer **extending an existing subject capsule** or **introducing a new folder under `app/src/components/<platform>/<subject>/`** (or another agreed subject root) over scattering helpers across unrelated trees.

## What a subject capsule contains

A subject directory should hold **the full vertical slice** for that concept whenever practical:

- **UI** (views, panels, components used primarily by that subject)
- **Behavior** (composables, hooks, runtimes)
- **Data access** (API client modules, repositories, Scribe/HTTP adapters)
- **Types & schemas** (subject-specific TS types, validation, DTOs)
- **Backend entrypoints** co-located when this repo already does so (e.g. `*.backend.ts` next to the subject it serves)

Avoid “find the logic in five folders” layouts for subject-owned features.

## This repository’s shape

- **PowerVibe** is organized as **subject-as-component** capsules under [`app/src/components/powervibe/`](app/src/components/powervibe/) — e.g. [`apps/`](app/src/components/powervibe/apps/) (app list / Scribe app API), [`ai/`](app/src/components/powervibe/ai/) (chat UI, chat repos; plan/ideation under [`ai/plan/`](app/src/components/powervibe/ai/plan/)), [`viewer/`](app/src/components/powervibe/viewer/) (preview, editor, materialized `generated/App.vue`), [`shell/`](app/src/components/powervibe/shell/) (workspace chrome). The orchestrating entry is [`powervibe.vue`](app/src/components/powervibe/powervibe.vue). **New PowerVibe behavior should default under the subject folder it belongs to**—not ad-hoc roots under `app/src/` without a subject story.
- Shared code used by **multiple** subjects may live in neutral homes (`app/src/lib/`, `shared/`) but should stay **thin**; subject-specific policy stays in the subject.

## When touching existing code

- Prefer edits **inside** the subject that owns the feature (e.g. PowerVibe chat → [`app/src/components/powervibe/ai/`](app/src/components/powervibe/ai/); ideation/plan API under [`app/src/components/powervibe/ai/plan/`](app/src/components/powervibe/ai/plan/)).
- Do **not** split one feature across distant folders unless there is a strong, documented reason (true cross-cutting infra belongs in `lib/` or `shared/` with minimal surface).

## Agents and collaboration

Treat subject folders as **boundaries**: infer context from the subject path, keep suggestions coherent within that capsule, and avoid cross-subject leaks unless the change is explicitly integration work.

## Discipline over dogma

Structure and consistency matter more than minor naming debates. If two reasonable subject names exist, pick the one that matches **how the team already speaks** about the product and stick to it.
